<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Unique, blueish (even somewhat iridescent in fresh specimens) black mimallonids usually with crenulated wing margins, broad wings; comparatively large antennae with some of the longest pectinations in 
<taxonomicName family="Mimallonidae" lsidName="" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" rank="family">Mimallonidae</taxonomicName>
(this trait is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="St Laurent, 2016" authorityName="St Laurent" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Cunicumara" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cunicumara" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cunicumara</taxonomicName>
). The toothed postmedial lines are inwardly lined with pale brown which contrasts against the dark ground color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="apomorphies">
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Apomorphies.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Lurama" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lurama" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Lurama</taxonomicName>
, but the combination of the following characters distinguishes 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Mimallonidae" genus="Ulmara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ulmara" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ulmara</taxonomicName>
: (1) gnathos present (Fig. 28a) and (2) sternite VIII with bilobed feet-like sclerotizations covered in elongate setae (Fig. 28b).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
